column168: ON JANUARY 23, 2002, KVS TRANSPORTATION PICKED UP A DRY VAN OF PRELOADED HAZARDOUS WASTE DRUMS (MANIFEST # 21064) AT EMERALD SERVICES IN TACOMA WASHINGTON. THE DRIVER STOPPED FOR LUNCH AND CHECKED HIS LOAD AT SINCLAIR TRUCKSTOP, JEROME, IDAHO (INTERSTATE 84, EXIT 168) AND NOTED A LEAKING DRUM 6 ROWS INTO THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER CONTACTED KVS DISPATCH AND A HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM WAS DISPATCHED. IN THE INTERIM, THE DRIVER SPREAD ABSORBANT ACCROSS THE BACK OF THE TRAILER TO PRECLUDE LEAKAGE ONTO THE GROUND. UPON ARRIVAL OF THE RESPONSE TEAM, THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED, THE TRAILER FIELD DECONTAMINATED AND THE  WASTE REMAINED ON THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE ENROUTE TO ITS ORIGINAL DISPOSAL DESTINATION IN INDIANA.

column168: ON FEBRUARY 9,2002, A KVS DRY VAN WAS DISPATCHED TO PACIFIC RESOURCE RECOVERY IN LOS ANGELES, CA. TO PICK UP A LOAD OF HAZARDOUS WASTE DRUMS FOR TRANSPORT AND DISPOSAL TO ROSS INCINERATION SERVICES IN GRAFTON OHIO. KVS DRIVER TIMOTHY MADDEN BACKED INTO THE LOADING AREA WHERE THE VAN WAS LOADED BY PACIFIC RESOURCE RECOVERY EMPLOYEES. THE TRUCK THEN PROCEEDED TO ITS DESTINATION. DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT EXIT 39 ON I-40, KVS DRIVER TIM MADDEN NOTED A RELEASE OF LIQUID FORM A DRUM FOUR ROWS INTO THE TRAILER AND CONTACTED KVS DISPATCH. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN THE TRAILER. A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR (ADVANCED ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES) WAS CALLED TO RESPOND. THE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED ON SITE AT APPROXIMATELY 1630  HOURS AND OVERPACKED THE LEAKING CONTAINER AND FIELD DECONTAMINATED THE TRAILER AND ITS CONTENTS. THE OVERPACKED DRUM WAS LEFT ON THE VEHICLE FOR DELIVERY TO THE ORIGINAL DESTINATION - ROSS INCINERATION SERVICES IN GRAFTON, OHIO WHERE IT WAS DELIVERED FEBRUARY 8, 2002.

UNIT 507-3300 WAS ASSIGNED TO THIS LOAD. WHEN UNIT ARRIVED FOR LOADING, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT IT NEEDED A PUMP. A PUMP WAS INSTALLED AT THE ST. GABRIEL TERMINAL AND THE TRAILER WENT TO LOAD. WHEN THE LOAD ARRIVED AT CAWTER INTL. TO UNLOAD, THE DRIVER CONNECTED HIS HOSE TO THE PUMP. HE TRIED TO PUMP OFF, BUT THE PUMP WAS CONNECTED BACKWARDS. column168: A SAFETY-KLEEN DRIVER WAS PERFORMING A MILK RUN BETWEEN LOCATIONS, WHILE AT THE CASEYVILLE, ILLINOIS FACILITY A PINHOLE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED ON A 55 GALLON METAL DRUM.  THE PINHOLE LEAK RELEASED APPROXIMATELY FIVE GALLONS OF MATERIAL ONTO THE TRUCK BED.  THE MATERIAL WAS CONFINED TO THE TRUCK BED. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED USING VERMICULITE WHICH WAS OVERPACKED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL DRUM INTO AN 85-GALLON OVERPACK CONTAINER.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY SIXTY-FIVE POUNDS OF WASTE, WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 633 EAST 138TH STREET IN DOLTON, ILLINOIS.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM INSPECTION AND HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ENSURE THAT NO FUTURE INCIDENTS WILL OCCUR.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WAS DISCOVERED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE CUP OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND WAS CONTAINED TO THE TOP OF THE DRUM.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE BUNG.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL B PROTECTION, AMPHOMAG, A WHISKBROOM AND DUSTPAN.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIFTEEN GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM AND ONE, TWENTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE LEAKING DRUM WITH REMAINING PRODUCT WAS PLACED INTO A SIXTY-FIVE GALLON OVERPACK DRUM.  BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS AND THE OVERPACK DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE ON THE DOCK, TERMINAL PERSONNEL DISCOVERED ONE WET FIBERBOARD CARTON CONTAINING TWELVE, ONE QUART PLASTIC JUGS.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE JUG WAS LEAKING AND THE OTHER ELEVEN WERE UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND ABSORBED BY THE CARTON.  THE DAMAGE TO THE JUG WAS CAUSED BY A SMALL PINHOLE LEAK WHICH WAS THE RESULT OF PACKAGING FAILURE.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, GOGGLES AND ABSORBENT PADS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND WET CARTON WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM. THE DAMAGED JUG WAS PLACED INTO A SEPARATE FIFTEEN GALLON FIBER PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  BOTH OF THE RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE ELEVEN UNAFFECTED JUGS WERE RECOUPED AND REPACKAGED AND WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING IN TRANSIT, CAUSING THE BOX TO FALL OFF THE SKID ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR, RUPTURING THE JUGS.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, BOOTIES, ABSORBENTS, A DUSTPAN AND WHISKBROOM.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, SATURATED BOX, AND TWO LEAKING JUGS WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE TWO AFFECTED JUGS WERE WIPED OFF, REPACKAGED, AND FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: DOCKWORKER STRIPPED OFF TRAILER AND NOTICE WET DRIPPINGS THAT WERE WHITE AND COMING FROM LID. THEY PUT SHIPMENT IN OSD. OSD EXAMINED AND SAW NO DAMAGE TO PAIL. THIS WAS A BLUE PAIL MADE OF PLASTIC AND HAD SMALL PLASTIC SCREW ON LID. TIGHTED UP LID. AND IT WAS ALREADY AS TIGHT AS POSSIBLE. PAIL STILL LEAKED. SO WE CALLED A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL COMPANY TO DISPOSE OF.

THIS INNER CONTAINER WITH DRY ICE RUPTURED DURING THE SORTING OPERATION AS A RESULT OF THE DRY ICE BEING PLACED INTO AN AIRTIGHT INNER PLASTIC CONTAINER.  PRESSURE APPARENTLY BUILT UP INSIDE THE PACKAGE CAUSING IT TO RUPTURE.  SEVERAL EMPLOYEES WHO WERE WORKING NEAR THE INCIDENT, AND AROUND THE PACKAGE WHEN IT RUPTURED, WERE SEEN BY A LOCAL HOSPITAL BECAUSE OF THE CONTENTS OF THE PACKAGE.  WHILE NO CONFIRMED EXPOSURES OCCURRED, AND ALL THE EMPLOYEES RETURNED TO WORK, THEY WERE PUT ON ANTIBIOTICS AS A PRECAUTION.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO THE FAA, CDC, AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER TO ADVISE THEM OF THE INCIDENT.  ONE PLASTIC VIAL WAS NEVER RECOVERED AND MAY HAVE BEEN DESTROYED AS A RESULT OF THE IMPACT.

THE TRUCK JACK KNIFED AND OVERTURNED ON TOP OF AN AUTOMOBILE. APPROXIMATELY ONE HUNDRED GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED FROM THE TOP MANWAY. THE PRINCE GEORGE'S COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT, THE MARYLAND STATE POLICE, THE MARYLAND ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY AND THE MARYLAND HIGHWAY DEPARTMENT ALL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT SECURED THE RELEASE AND A ENVIRONMENTAL OF BALTIMORE, MD WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. column168: OUTBOUND DRIVER REPORTED CONTAINER LEAKING & IT WAS DRIVEN TO CONTAINMENT AREA.  BNSF CONTRACT RESPONDERS FOUND THREE DRUMS ON TOP TIER THAT WERE DAMAGED & LEAKED.  ONE DRUM CONTAINING PG II MATERIAL HAD A TOP ROLLING HOOP CRACK & LEAKED AN ESTIMATED 15 GALLONS.  THE OTHER TWO DRUMS OF PG III MATERIAL LEAKED AS ONE DRUM HAD THE LID PRIED OFF BY AN ADJACENT DRUM'S RING BOLT & LOST AN ESTIMATED 15 GALLONS.  THE OTHER HAD A SMALL ABRASION CRACK AT THE BOTTOM CHIME LOSING AN ESTIMATED 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  ALL FAILURES RESULTED FROM INSUFFICIENT BLOCKING & BRACING COMBINED WITH IMPROPER LOADING OF THE DRUMS INSIDE THE CONTAINER, ALLOWING TOP TIER DRUMS TO ROTATE & RUB AGAINST ONE ANOTHER.  SPILLED PRODUCT ATOP PAVEMENT IN TRAILER LOT CLEANED.  SPILLED PRODUCT INSIDE CONTAINER HAD DRIED & MOSTLY SCRAPED OFF.  THE DAMAGED DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED & RETURNED TO LOAD AFTER ADJUSTMENTS TO LADING MADE.

THE AMPHO-MAG WAS PLACED INTO A SEPARATE TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE LEAKING JUG AND WET BOX WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  ALL THREE RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING, TWO THOUSAND POUND STEEL TOTE WAS DISCOVERED AT THE THIRD-QUARTER MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY, ONE PINT OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE VALVE.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING ABSORBENTS, SUITS AND GOGGLES.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE VALVE WAS TIGHTENED ON THE LEAKING TOTE AND IT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, FIVE DAMAGED CARTONS EACH CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WERE DISCOVERED AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE JUG WAS DAMAGED AND THE REMAINING NINETEEN JUGS WERE UNAFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY THREE QUARTERS OF A GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED, ABSORBED BY THE CARTONS AND EVAPORATED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PACKAGE FAILURE, ONE JUG HAD A BUBBLE ON IT, WHICH ENDED UP BURSTING.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FIVE AFFECTED CARTONS WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE DAMAGED JUG WAS PLACED INTO A TWELVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM AND THE REMAINING NINETEEN JUGS WERE PLACED INTO AN EIGHTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  THESE TWO RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER, PER THEIR INSTRUCTIONS. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OF EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

DRIVER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING PRODUCT FROM THE CARGO TANK INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK VIA USE OF A TRACTOR MOUNTED PRODUCT TRANSFER PUMP. A SEAL ON PUMP WHERE THE DRIVER SHAFT CONNECTS TO IT FAILED DURING UNLOADING RESULTING IN 2 GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLING ONTO THE GROUND BEFORE THE DRIVER COULD GET THE PUMP SHUT OFF. ON FEBRUARY 21, 2002 A LOAD OF CUBIC YARD BOXES OF SHREDDER RESIDUE FROM SUPERIOR SPECIAL SERVICES' MERCURY RECOVERY FACILITY IN PHOENIX WAS BEING DELIVERED TO SAFETY-KLEEN, LAWRENCE MA. WHILE UNLOADING, ELEMENTAL MERCURY WAS DISCOVERED ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. THE TRAILER WAS EQUIPPED WITH A SECONDARY CONTAINMENT SYSTEM/SPILL PAN. MERCURY ABSORBENT POWDER WAS APPLIED TO THE MATERIAL TO ENSURE THAT THE MERCURY WOULD  REMAIN CONTAINED WITHIN THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT SYSTEM. ALL CONTAINERS WERE SECURED ON THE TRAILER AND THE LOAD WAS TRANSPORTED TO SUPERIOR SPECIAL SERVICES FACILITY IN PORT WASHINGTON, WI WHERE WE HAD THE PERSONNEL AND ADEQUATE FACILITIES TO PERFORM THE CLEAN UP. UPON ARRIVAL, THE TRAILER WAS OFF-LOADED AND DECONTAMINATED. THE CONTAINERS THAT WERE OFF-LOADED WERE INSPECTED FOR ANY VISUAL EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE OR PACKAGE FAILURE. NO ONE INDIVIDUAL CONTAINER WAS FOUND TO HAVE ANY VISUAL EVIDENCE OF FAILURE OR LEAKAGE. THE CONTAINERS WERE RELOADED AND THE LOAD WAS TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE FACILITY THAT ORIGINATED THE SHIPMENT. BECAUSE OF THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT SYSTEM IN THE TRAILER THERE WAS NO RELEASE TO THE ENVIRONMENT. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SHIPPERS FACILITY, THE CONTAINERS WERE REPACKAGED AND ONE OF THE BOXES WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN MERCURY SWITCHES THAT HAD NOT DRAINED DURING THE SHREDDING PROCESS AND MANY OF THESE WITCHES APPEARED TO HAVE BROKEN AND RELEASED THERE CONTENTS DURING SHIPMENT.

DRIVER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING PRODUCT FROM THE CARGO TANK INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK VIA USE OF A TRACTOR MOUNTED PRODUCT TRANSFER PUMP. A SEAL ON PUMP WHERE THE DRIVE SHAFT CONNECTS TO IT FAILED DURING UNLOADING RESULTING IN 2 GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLING ONTO THE GROUND BEFORE THE DRIVER COULD GET THE PUMP SHUT OFF. THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP BY PLANT PERSONNEL AND PROPERTY DISPOSED OF. CAUSE OF THE SEAL FAILURE WAS DETERMINED TO BE FROM EXCESSIVE VIBRATION OF THE PTO SHAFT DRIVING THE PUMP. THIS WAS CORRECTED BY PLACING A SLIP JOINT IN THE DRIVE SHAFT TO ABSORB ANY VIBRATION GENERATED AS THE PUMP WAS OPERATING DURING UNLOADING.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING THIS TRAILER A WALL MADE OUT OF PLYWOOD WAS REMOVED. WHEN THIS WALL WAS GONE OUR NOSE, EYES AND SKID IMMEDIATELY BECAME IRRITATED. WE BEGAN TO COUGH AND GAG. WE IMMEDIATELY SHUT THE TRAILER DOOR PULLED THIS TRAILER OUT TO A WELL VENTILATED ARE IN THE YARD AWAY FROM PEOPLE AND ANIMALS. CALL OUR SAFETY SUPERVISOR FOR FURTHER DIRECTION AND HE IN TURN CALLED SOONER ENVIRONMENTAL. THEY ASSESSED THE SCENE AND IDENTIFIED THE LEAKING CYLINDER. AT THIS TIME IT WAS DEEMED SAFE TO RETURN TO WORK. THE CYLINDER WAS NOT PROPERLY CLOSED (VALVE) AND THE SAFETY CAP WAS LOOSE. THIS ALLOWED THE GAS TO ESCAPE. IN COMBINATION WITH WATER THAT WAS INSIDE THE CARTON FROM WHERE THE SHIPPER LEFT PACKAGE OUT IN THE WEATHER. WHEN THE GAS MADE CONTACT  WITH THE WATER FORMED A ASCETIC POISON GAS. THIS CREATED THE IRRITATION AS NOTED ABOVE. NO OTHER CARGO WAS CONTAMINATED AND THE FUMES WERE CONTAINED TO THE SPACE OF THE TRAILER.

column42: ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, N.O.S., AT OR ABOVE 100 C AND BELOW ITS FLASH POINT (INCLUDING MOLTEN METALS, MOLTEN SALTS, ETC.)
column168: THE FOLLOW IS A DESCRIPTION OF EVENTS ON FEBRUARY 4, 2002 AT 15:27 REGARDING AN ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, N.O.S., 9, UN3257, PG III SPILL ON BROOKLYN BLVD./MNTH 100.  THE RELEASE FROM BULK PACKAGE RESULTED FROM A CHEMICAL REACTION INSIDE THE CARGO TANK FROM SOLIDIFIED MOISTURE (ICE) AND ROOFING ASPHALT.  WHEN TANKER TRAILERS ARE NOT USED FOR AN EXTENDED PERIOD OF TIME, MOISTURE CAN COLLECT INSIDE THE TANKS.  WHEN THE DRIVER FILLS A TANK THEY DO A TEST FILL, WHERE THE OPERATOR PUTS 200 GALLONS OF ROOFING ASPHALT AT 400 F INTO THE TANK TO SEE IF THERE IS ANY REACTION.  THE MATERIAL IS THEN ALLOWED TO STAND FOR 10 MINUTES TO MAKE SURE THERE IS NO MOISTURE OR ICE INSIDE THE TANK.  THIS WAS DONE WITHOUT ANY REACTION.  THE OPERATOR THEN FILLED THE TANK, AND THE DRIVER LEFT THE FACILITY.  THE DRIVER WAS APPROXIMATELY 5 MILES DOWN THE ROAD, AND NOTICED STEAM ESCAPING FROM THE OVERFLOW AREA.  HE REALIZED WHAT WAS HAPPENING AND GOT THE TRUCK OFF THE ROAD AND ONTO THE SHOULDER NEAR THE DITCH.  THE MOISTURE AND ASPHALT REACTED CAUSING THE MATERIAL TO EXPAND CAUSING AN OVERFLOW OF ASPHALT FROM THE TANKER.  THIS CONTINUED UNTIL ALL MOISTURE HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TANK.  APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS OF THE ASPHALT DRAINED INTO THE DITCH AREA.  UPON COOLING, E. R. BERWALD ROOFING CO., INC. USED SKID STEER LOADERS TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED ASPHALT.  IN THE FUTURE THE DRIVERS WILL WAIT AN ADDITIONAL 10 MINUTES AT THE MANUFACTURER'S FACILITY WHEN THE TANK IS FULL TO ENSURE NO REACTION IS TAKING PLACE BEFORE LEAVING.  OUR ACCIDENT INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT ICE WAS INSIDE THE TANK, AND WAS ENVELOPED BY ASPHALT DURING THE TEST FILL.  THIS PREVENTED THE ICE FROM MELTING QUICKLY, THUS POSTPONING CHEMICAL REACTION.  THE ADDITIONAL WAIT TIME BEFORE THE DRIVER LEAVES WITH THE ASPHALT SHOULD PREVENT THE ACCIDENTAL RELEASE OF ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, N.O.S., 9, UN3257, PG III, FROM HAPPENING AGAIN.  KEVIN KAMPA, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST PERFORMED A COMPLIANCE REVIEW ON MAY 29-30.  IT WAS DURING THIS MEETING THAT E. R. BERWALD ROOFING CO, INC. BECAME AWARE OF THE DOT FORM 5800.1.  WHEN INFORMED OF THE REPORT, E. R. BERWALD ROOFING CO., INC. IMMEDIATELY FILED IT WITH THE OFFICE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TRANSPORTATION.

SCBA WASN'T USED DUE TO THE LACK OF AN IRRITATING ODOR AND BUILDING VENTILATION. COMPLETE PARCEL SENT ON TO ITS DESTINATION. RECOMMEND CUSHIONING BE ADDED TO BOX TO ABSORB THE SHOCKS OF TRANSPORT.

DECISION TREE AND THE RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLES USE FOR PROCESS SPILL THROUGH DMP. CLAY WAS USED TO CONTAIN AND ABSORB SPILL. I RESPONDED TO A SPILL ON THE ORANGE BELT. I USE THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR UNKNOWN. RESPONSE SHEET FOR UNKNOWN HAD ME PERFORM A LITMUS TEST. LITMUS TEST READ PH BALANCE NEUTRAL RANGE. RESPONSE SHEET AND RESULT OF LITMUS TEST HAD ME USE RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID. RESPONSE SHEET FOR ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS PLACE IN A LINED SPILL TRAY AND AFTERWARDS ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS TAKEN TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. PROPER PACKAGE HANDLING WOULD HAVE PREVENTED THE SPILL. THE REMAINING 95 ITEMS WERE SENT TO THE CONSIGNEE IN EXCELLENT CONDITION.

I RESPONDED TO A SPILL ON THE BLACK BELT. I USE THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR ORMD. RESPONSE SHEET FOR ORMD HAD ME PERFORM A LITMUS TEST. LITMUS TEST READ PH BALANCE 1 RANGE. RESPONSE SHEET AND RESULT OF LITMUS TEST HAD ME USE RESPONSE SHEET FOR CORROSIVE LIQUID. SHEET FOR CORROSIVE LIQUID HAD ME CAREFULLY APPLY SODIUM BICARBONATE. I RETESTED THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL TO RE INSURE THAT THE PH BALANCE WAS WITHIN THE RANGE OF BETWEEN 6-9. CLAY ABSORBENT WAS ALSO USE TO CONTAIN THE REMAINING CONTAMINATED LIQUID. ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS PLACE IN A LINED SPILL TRAY AND AFTERWARD. ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS TAKEN TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. A TIGHTEN CAP COULD HAVE PREVENTED THE SPILL. THE REMAINING 5 PLASTIC CONTAINERS WERE SENT TO THE CONSIGNEE IN EXCELLENT CONDITION.

column168: OPERATORS WERE ASSIGNED A WORK ORDER TO LOAD A TANK TRUCK WITH PERCHLOROETHYLENE AT THE DOW TRUCK RACK FROM STORAGE TANK 150-21. THE WORK ORDER INDICATED THAT THE TRUCK WAS TO BE FILLED WITH 46,000 POUNDS OF PRODUCT. THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT TO BE TRANSFERRED WAS LATER CHANGED TO 45,000 POUNDS. INFORMATION AS TO THE POUNDS PER GALLON OF PRODUCT WAS INDICATED IN THE REMARKS SECTION OF THE ORDER. OPERATOR#1 SET THE FLOW METER TO LOAD THE TRUCK WITH 45,000 GALLONS OF PRODUCT. THE RELIEF FOREMAN ON DUTY CHECKED THE LINE UP AND HE GAVE OK TO OPERATORS TO START PUMPING. AFTER ABOUT 20 MINUTES OF PUMPING, THE OPERATORS NOTICED PRODUCT FLOWING OUT OF THE TOP HATCH OF THE TANK TRUCK. OPERATORS SHUT DOWN THE TRANSFER AND NOTIFIED THE FOREMAN ON DUTY. THIS INCIDENT RESULTED IN A PRODUCT SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF PERCHLOROETHYLENE. SINCE PERCHLOROETHYLENE HAS A REPORTABLE QUANTITY(RQ) OF 11 GALLONS, ALL APPROPRIATE GOVERNMENT AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE.

column168: ON THURSDAY, FEBRUARY 28, 2002 AT APPROXIMATELY 5:30 A.M. CHARLES BARRAND, OUR TRUCK DRIVER CAME INTO THE RECEIVING OFFICE AND INFORMED ME, RICH PETZ, THAT OUR HYDROCHLORIC ACID TANKER WHICH WAS HOOKED TO #1 PETERBILT TRACTOR WAS STOPPED IN FRONT OF OUR NEIGHBORS, TARCO CONSTRUCTION, AND HYDROCHLORIC ACID WAS LEAKING OUT OF THE TANKER ON TO THE STREET. WE RAN OUT TO THE TANKER AND I WENT IMMEDIATELY TO THE UNLOAD VALVE, FOUND THAT IT WAS IN THE OPEN POSITION WITH HYDROCHLORIC ACID COMING OUT OF THE UNLOADING LINE. I SCREWED THE VALVE TO THE CLOSED POSITION STOPPING HYDROCHLORIC ACID FROM LEAKING OUT. I THEN INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER, CHARLES BARRAND, TO TAKE THE TRACTOR-TRAILER OFF OF THE STREET, AND GO TO THE LOADING SCALE WHERE THERE IS CONTAINMENT AND WASH THE ENTIRE TRACTOR-TRAILER DOWN WITH WATER. I THEN INSTRUCTED JESUS BARRERA TO PUT A MAN ON EACH END OF THE SPILL TO STOP ALL TRAFFIC. WE THEN LOADED 1,000 GALLONS OF FRESH WATER ON TO #18 OUR INTERNATIONAL TANK TRUCK AND MYSELF AND JUAN TREJO DROVE TO THE POINT OF THE SPILL AND PROCEEDED TO PUT THE WATER ON TO THE SPILL IN ORDER TO KNOCK DOWN THE HYDROCHLORIC ACID FUMES WHICH I FELT AT THAT TIME WAS THE BIGGEST AREA  OF CONCERN AS THE FUMES COULD DRIFT AND BE INHALED CREATING A HAZARD. IT WAS APPROXIMATELY 6:00 A.M. AT THIS TIME. WE WORKED OUR WAY FROM THE WEST TO THE EAST KEEPING THE WATER ON THE HYDROCHLORIC ACID AHEAD OF US. WE THEN REFILLED THE TANKER WITH 2,000 GALLONS OF FRESH WATER AND STARTED THE PROCEDURE ALL OVER AGAIN. ONCE I REALIZED WE WERE GAINING ON THE FUMES, I PHONED THE PRESIDENT OF THE COMPANY, ROBERT L WILSON II, AND OUR MATERIAL/REGULATIONS MANAGER, ALAN BIESEMEIER. OUR NEIGHBOR, TARCO CONSTRUCTION CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THEY HAD ARRIVED ON THE EAST SIDE OF THE SPILL. APPROXIMATELY 30 MINUTES HAD ELAPSED SINCE WE STARTED TO PUT THE WATER ON THE SPILL. WHILE PLANT PERSONNEL WAS PUTTING ON MORE AND MORE WATER TO HELP DILUTE THE HYDROCHLORIC ACID, I SPOKE WITH THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND EXPLAINED TO THEM WHAT HAD HAPPENED AND EXACTLY WHAT WE HAD DONE FROM THE TIME THE SPILL HAD STARTED TO THE PRESENT TIME. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS VERY PLEASED WITH WHAT WE HAD DONE AND THEY CONTACTED THE FIRE CHIEF, MR. GEORGE DITOLLA, TO ASK WHETHER HE FELT THEY SHOULD CALL OUT THE LOCAL EMERGENCY HAZARDOUS RESPONSE TEAM. GARY ARMADA MADE THE DECISION NOT TO CALL OUT THE TEAM WITH THE INFORMATION PROVIDED TO HIM BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL ON SCENE. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT THEN ASSISTED US IN APPLYING MORE WATER TO DILUTE THE SPILL. AT THIS POINT IN TIME THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ASKED IF WE COULD MAKE A DETERMINATION ON HOW BIG A SPILL WE HAD. WE WEIGHTED THE TRACTOR-TRAILER AND COMPARED THAT WEIGHT(SEE ATTACHED) WITH THE ORIGINAL SCALE TICKET SHOWING WHAT PRODUCT WAS ON BOARD. WE DETERMINED THAT WE HAD LOST 140 POUNDS, WHICH IS APPROXIMATELY 14.6 GALLONS AT 34% STRENGTH 31.4 HYDROCHLORIC ACID. WE GAVE THAT INFORMATION AND COPIES OF THE WEIGHT TICKETS TO THE FIRE DEPARTMENT. AT THIS TIME WE

FUEL SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITH FLOOR-DRY MATERIAL AND PICKED UP BY THE CARRIER FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. NEW DRIVER WAS TRAINED IN PROPER OFF-LOADING PROCEDURES FOR THIS SITE.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS LOADING A TOTE OF SULFURIC ACID ONTO HIS SHORT BED RACK TRUCK INSIDE OUR WAREHOUSE WHEN LEAK OCCURRED. I BELIEVE THAT HE WAS PUSHING TOTE ALONG THE BED OF THE TRUCK WITH THE FORKS OF THE LIFT TRUCK, AT SOME POINT THE TOTE STOPPED SLIDING AND THE FORK OF LIFT TRUCK SLID THROUGH THE BOTTOM OF OUTER CAGE STRIKING THE VALVE ON BOTTOM OF THE TOTE. THE VALVE STARTED LEAKING AT THIS POINT, AREA WAS DIKED OFF AND SULFURIC DEACTIVATED WITH A COMBINATION OF SODIUM BICARBONATE AND LIME. THE DEACTIVATED MATERIAL WAS TESTED UNTIL PH WAS NEUTRAL AND THEN DISPOSED OF. DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER HANDLING OF TOTES.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 3:00 PM A TRACTOR-TRAILER TRUCK WAS PARKED AT OUR UNLOADING DOCK AND WE WERE IN THE PROCESS OF HOOKING A CHAIN TO THE PALLET TO PULL IT OUT OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER WENT BACK TO HIS TRUCK AND WAS ATTEMPTING TO MOVE TO ANOTHER DOCK DOOR WHEN THE PALLET WITH ONE METRIC TON OF COOPER SULFATE PENTAHYDRATE, FELL OUT OF THE TRUCK. THE BULK BAG SPLIT AND APPROXIMATELY TWENTY (20) POUNDS RELEASED FROM THE BAG. OUR WAREHOUSE OPERATIONS MANAGER, CHARLIE ROSS AND I INSTRUCTED THREE WAREHOUSEMAN TO CONTAIN THE AREA. THEY IMMEDIATELY PLACED ABSORBENT SACKS AROUND THE BULK BAG TO PREVENT ANY RUN OFF. EACH WAREHOUSEMAN BEGAN SHOVELING THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND THE MATERIAL IN THE TORN  BULK BAG INTO AN EMPTY BULK BAG. PLASTIC SHEETS WERE PLACED UNDER THE EMPTY BULK BAG TO PREVENT RUNOFF. OF THE TOTAL 2204.6 POUNDS IN THE BULK BAG, 2184.6 POUNDS WAS PUT IN THE NEW BULK BAG SEVENTEEN (17) POUNDS WAS GATHERED AND WILL BE SOLD AS RECOVERED PRODUCT TO A DISTRIBUTOR. THE INTEGRITY OF THE PRODUCT IS INTACT. THE REMAINING PRODUCT THAT IS CONTAMINATED, WHICH WE QUANTIFIED AT THREE(3) POUNDS, WILL BE DISPOSED OF PROPERLY THROUGH OUR DISPOSAL COMPANY. PREVENTATIVE MEASURE FOR THE FUTURE WILL BE TO HAVE THE TRUCK DRIVER TURN OFF THEIR ENGINE.

column168: FILE: 2185 D. SHIPPER: BAUSCH & LOMB AWB# 8RQ 8734981133 NSH.  ON 02/05/2002 AT 00:49 A CALL CAME IN THAT THERE WAS A PACKAGE LEAKING A RED "C" CONTAINER AT DOOR D-10 WITH ONE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC, 146 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON , OHIO, 45177.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS DONALD OSBORNE AND ALAN HENDERSON RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THE SPILL TECHS NOTICED THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION AND THAT IT WAS APPROXIMATELY 95% SATURATED BY A LIQUID.  THE PACKAGE WAS REMOVED FROM THE "C" CONTAINER AND OPENED IT DISCOVERING THAT THE INNER BROWN GLASS RECEPTACLE WAS WET AND THAT THE STYROFOAM PEANUTS INSIDE APPEARED TO BE DISSOLVING AND STICKING TO THE BROWN GLASS RECEPTACLE.  ALSO NOTICED WAS A RIGHT-TO-KNOW LABEL WITH THE DESCRIPTION "T-BUTYL PEROCTOATE" AND DANGER WARNING INDICATED BY AN "X" NEXT TO THE FOLLOWING: COMBUSTIBLE, OXIDIZER, EXPLOSIVE AND IRRITANT.  THIS LABEL ALSO INDICATED THE PERSON HANDLING THIS MATERIAL SHOULD WEAR THE FOLLOWING PRODUCT EQUIPMENT: EYE PROTECTION, GLOVES, USE IN A WELL VENTILATED AREA AND WEAR A LAB COAT OR APRON.  THE SPILL TECHNICIANS PLACED THE INNER BROWN GLASS RECEPTACLE BACK INTO THE PACKAGE AND NOTED THAT ON EACH SIDE OF THE OUTER MOST PACKAGING WAS PINK STICKERS INDICATING "FRAGILE" AND ALSO THERE WAS A BAUSCH AND LOMB WHITE STICKER INDICATING "THIS PACKAGE CONFORMS TO THE CONDITIONS AND LIMITATIONS SPECIFIED IN 49CFR 173.4" AND THE NAME FRED PNANEUF.  THIS MAY HAVE BEEN AN OLD LABEL SINCE THE QUANTITY SHIPPED EXCEEDED WHAT IS ALLOWED, BUT IN THIS CASE THIS PRODUCT IS FORBIDDEN IN ANY QUANTITY FOR PASSENGER OR CARGO AIRCRAFT AND NO EXCEPTIONS APPLY ACCORDING TO 49CFR 172.101 TABLES. THE SPILL TECHNICIANS DOUBLE BAGGED THIS SHIPMENT ADDING ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND THEN PLACED IT INTO A UN SPECIFICATION  SALVAGE DRUM AND STORED IT OUTSIDE IN A TRAILER SINCE ALL INFORMATION INDICATED THAT AT 80 DEGREES FARENHEIT IT WILL EXPLODE.  THEREFORE ALL PRECAUTIONS WERE TAKEN TO REDUCE THIS RISK PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THE EMPLOYEE INVOLVED WAS ADVISED OF WHAT THEY HAD BEEN EXPOSED TO.  THE EMPLOYEE DID NOT REQUIRE ANY MEDICAL ATTENTION AND RETURNED TO WORK, NO MEDICAL FOLLOWED WAS REQUIRED.  THIS SHIPMENT DID NOT HAVE ANY MARKINGS, LABELS, OR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 01:14.

PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS JEFF KIDDER AND BETH PARKER RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THE SPILL TECHNICIANS NOTED A STRONG ODOR AND DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, AND RESUMED INVESTIGATING THE SHIPMENT AND FOUND A SILVERY WHITE FLAKING NEAR THE BOTTOM OF THE CHIPBOARD TYPE WOOD BOX, BANDED BY TWO PLASTIC BANDING STRIPS.  THE SPILL TECHNICIANS OPENED THE BOX AND DISCOVERED 10 X 1 KG EACH METAL CANS, OF "ALUMINUM PASTE-7510" EACH WERE SECURED BY 2 METAL CLIPS.  THE SPILL TECHNICIANS ALSO NOTED THAT ONE OF THE LIDS ON METAL CAN WAS LOOSE RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 30 GRAMS OF ITS CONTENTS.  THERE WASN'T ANY ABSORBENT MATERIAL USED AND VERY LITTLE CUSHIONING MATERIAL TO PREVENT THE MOVEMENT OF THE METAL CANS WITHIN THE WOOD BOX.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH AN ABSORBENT PAD AND TAKEN BACK TO OUR HAZ SORT FACILITY AND PLACED INTO A UN SPECIFICATION SALVAGE DRUM TO BE HELD PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  ACCORDING TO THE INTERNATIONAL AIR WAYBILL, SHIPPING INVOICE AND TEST REPORT THERE WERE TWO BOXES ONE OF WHICH CONTAINED 5 X 1 KG EACH METAL CANS OF "ALUMINUM PASTE-MT 7512" IT IS UNKNOWN AT THIS TIME WHERE THE SECOND PART IS. CONTRARY TO THE INVOICE WHICH STATED THAT THE SAMPLES "ALUMINUM PASTE-MT 7510 & ALUMINUM PASTE MT 7512" ARE NON-DANGEROUS, ACCORDING TO THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET THE FLASH POINT IS LESS THAN 35 DEGREES C. WHICH INDICATES THAT THE PRODUCT IS "FLAMMABLE".  THERE WAS ONE EMPLOYEE THAT NOTICED THE ODOR BRIEFLY AND NO MEDICAL ATTENTION OR FOLLOW UP WAS NECESSARY, ONCE THE SHIPMENT WAS REMOVED FROM THE AREA THE EMPLOYEE RESUMED WORK.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WAS A REGULATED MATERIAL.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 04:10

LANE A. SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED BY RMCC OF A LEAKING TANK CAR OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID AT THE CAR SHOP AT 18TH STREET YARD. ON ARRIVAL, MR. SEKAVEC MADE AN ASSESSMENT OF THE CAR AND DETERMINED THE LEAK ORIGINATED FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. PRODUCT HAD RUN DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CAR AND A ONE-INCH DIAMETER PUDDLE HAD DROPPED ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE CAR SHOP. THE CAR HAD BEEN MOVED OUTSIDE THE SHOP PRIOR TO MR. SEKAVEC'S ARRIVAL AND INVESTIGATION REVEALED NO PRODUCT ON THE GROUND. THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND STUFFING BOX FOR THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WERE BOTH CHECKED WITH NO APPARENT LEAKS NOTED. THE MANWAY WAS OPENED, AS IT APPEARED THAT THE GASKET WAS NOT MAINTAINING A PROPER SEAL. A NEW GASKET WAS FORMED FROM GORETEX GASKET MATERIAL AND INSTALLED AND THE MANWAY WAS SECURED. NO OTHER PROBLEMS WERE NOTED WITH THE CAR AND IT WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.  THE PUDDLE INSIDE THE CAR SHOP WAS ABSORBED AND THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN THE CAR PRIOR TO CLOSURE. SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF CONTAMINATED MATERIAL IN THE TANK CAR.

THE TANKCAR WAS LOCATED IN YARD 1 IN TRACK 872. DUFFY EXON, MANAGER FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND CONTRACTED WITH ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE INCORPORATED TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT. THE CONTRACTOR DETERMINED THAT THE TANKCAR HAD FOUR OUT OF SIX MANWAY BOLTS LOOSE, WITH ONE THAT WAS UNATTACHED COMPLETELY. THE  MANWAY BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED DOWN AND TANKCAR SHPX 202445 WAS RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AND A COURTESY NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO THE STATE.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: STEVE HAMPTON, MANAGER OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS, REPORTED A MINIMAL AMOUNT OF DENATURED ALCOHOL WAS RELEASED FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE OF TANKCAR GATX 21231. MR. HAMPTON STATED THE SUBSTANCE WAS RELEASING AT APPROXIMATELY EIGHT TO NINE DROPS PER MINUTE AND THE TANKCAR HAD BEEN ISOLATED ON YARD ONE TRACK SEVEN AT THE PHOENIX YARD. THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND NO WATERWAYS WERE EFFECTED. DUFFY EXON, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND DISPATCHED A CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND. MANAGER EXON WAS ADVISED BY THE CONTRACTOR THAT THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS IN THE OPEN POSITION, THE TWO INCH LINE WAS OPEN, AND THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE LOOSE. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AND COURTESY NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO THE APPROPRIATE STATE AGENCIES.

column168: JEFF WALKER, MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED TANKCAR TILX 190013 HAD LEAKED AN KNOWN AMOUNT OF PRODUCT FROM THE TOP DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS IN THE ALFALFA YARD. MR.WALKER FURTHER STATED NO ONE WAS INJURED AND THE TANKCAR WAS ISOLATED IN YARD 6 ON TRACK 7. CHEMTREC NOTIFICATION WAS MADE. JOHN JACKSON, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND HE RESPONDED. MGR. JACKSON REPLACED A MANWAY GASKET AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED. A COURTESY STATE NOTIFICATION WAS ALSO MADE.

column168: C.E. HARRIS, CAR FOREMAN, REPORTED TANKCAR GATX 37673 WAS LEAKING AN OILY SUBSTANCE FROM THE TOP AND IT HAD GOTTEN ALL OVER THE SAFETY APPLIANCES. THE CAR WAS LOCATED ON TRACK 204 AT THE WEST COLTON RECEIVING FACILITY. MR. HARRIS REPORTED THAT APPROXIMATELY TWO TO THREE GALLONS HAD LEAKED ONTO THE GROUND. ROBERT BAVIER, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED. DUFFY EXON, MANAGER FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. MGR. EXON DETERMINED THAT TANKCAR GATX37673 WOULD HAVE TO BE OFFLOADED DUE TO THE EXTREMELY OVERLOADED CONDITION. MR. EXON ALSO FOUND THAT THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE LOOSE. ALL NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE BY RMCC. ASBERRY ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTRACTED TO HANDLE THE CLEANUP. MGR. EXON CLOSED AND TIGHTENED THE MANWAY COVER. THE TANK CAR WAS MOVED TO THE RIP TRACK FOR WASHING AND OVERLOAD REDUCTION.

column42: MATCHES, SAFETY (BOOK, CARD OR STRIKE ON BOX
column168: A PASSENGER'S BAG WAS OBSERVED SMOLDERING AT DFW AIRPORT, TERMINAL C BAGGAGE ENCODER ROOM AND REPORTED TO AN AMERICAN AIRLINES CUSTOMER SERVICE MANAGER. THE MANAGER FOUND A BOOK OF SAFETY MATCHES HAD IGNITED IN A BAG BELONGING TO JEAN CHRISTOPHE SAUVAT. A LOCAL PASSENGER WHO HAD CHECKED-IN ON FLIGHT AA722 DFW-LGA.  THE MANAGER EXTINGUISHED THE SMOLDERING MATCHES AND NOTIFIED THE AMERICAN AIRLINES TOWER REQUESTING ENVIRONMENTAL COORDINATOR ASSISTANCE. THE PASSENGER, AT FRENCH NATIONAL,  WAS INTERVIEWED BY THE ENVIRONMENTAL COORDINATOR AND BOTH OF HIS CHECKED BAGS EXAMINED FOR FURTHER DANGEROUS GOODS/PROHIBITED ITEMS. ONE ADDITIONAL PACK OF SAFETY MATCHES WAS LOCATED IN A SHAVING KIT AND CONFISCATED. THE PASSENGERS' ID COPY AND ADDRESS INFORMATION WAS OBTAINED FOR FAA REPORTING AND THE PASSENGER WAS EDUCATED ON HIDDEN DANGEROUS GOODS REGULATIONS.
column172: Packages or containers checked on board an aircraft by a passenger in addition to luggage

column168: FILE: 2186 D SHIPPER: SIGMA ALDRICH CHEMICAL, INC., AWB #MKE 46080203486 MMR. ON 2/25/2002, AT 01:13 AN ODOR WAS CALLED IN AT THE HAZ SORT BUILDING ON LINE 4, BUILDING 208 OF OUR FACILITY LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO, 45177. PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS JEFFERY KIDDER AND THOMAS CASPER DONNED THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND ENTERED THE AREA TO INVESTIGATE WHAT WAS CAUSING THE ODOR. USING A VOC MONITOR TO DETECT WHICH PACKAGE AMONG NUMEROUS PACKAGES WAS ACTUALLY EMITTING THE ODOR, THE ABOVE PACKAGE WAS IDENTIFIED AS EMITTING AN ODOR. THE SPILL TECHNICIANS REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE IMMEDIATE AREA AND TOOK IT BACK TO A WELL VENTILATED REPACK ROOM AND OPENED THE PACKAGE FINDING INSIDE A PLASTIC BAG TIED OFF, BUT LEAKAGE INSIDE OF THE PLASTIC BAG WAS NOTED. FURTHER INVESTIGATION FOUND THAT THE CLOSURE WAS LOOSE ATTRIBUTING TO THE LEAKAGE AND THE PACKAGE EMITTING AN ODOR.  ONCE CONFIRMED THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A UN SPECIFICATION SALVAGE DRUM PENDING FILING OF THIS REPORT AND RETURN AUTHORIZATION FROM THE SHIPPER.  THERE WAS ONE EMPLOYEE WHO BRIEFLY NOTICED THE ODOR AND REPORTED IT. THIS EMPLOYEE DID NOT REQUIRE MEDICAL ATTENTION AND RETURNED TO WORK WHEN THE SHIPMENT WAS REMOVED FROM THE AREA. NO MEDICAL FOLLOW-UP WAS REQUIRED. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND WAS ACCOMPANYIED BY A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS.

IMPROPER BLOCKING BY BRADFORD @LJS, THE SHIPPER'S BASIC PACKAGING MATERIAL FAILED (THE PALLET BROKE) AND IN RESULT THE PAILS WERE PUNCTURED AND SPILLED. JOHN W/CHEMTREC AND LONNIE BENNETT, SAFETY SUPERVISOR WAS CONTACTED AND A COPY OF THE REPORT WAS SENT TO LJ'S SCM TONY DILLARDS.

PACKAGE HAD AN ODOR AT DESTINATION AND WAS OPENED.  FOUND 3 BOTTLES OF A TYPE OF NAIL POLISH EACH WITH A CAPACITY OF APPROXIMATELY 15 ML.  THE BOTTLES INDICATED TO KEEP AWAY FROM FLAME AND HEAT SO AN MSDS WAS REQUESTED FROM THE SHIPPER.  AFTER A WEEK AND NO MSDS THE PACKAGE WAS TURNED IN TO THE APPROPRIATE AUTHORITY TO INVESTIGATE AS A POSSIBLE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOOD.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING DURING THE PACKAGE SORTING OPERATION.  ONE OF THE INNER CONTAINERS WAS FOUND TO HAVE LEAKED DUE TO A LOOSE CLOSURE.  WITH NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKING, LABELING, OR PAPERWORK WITH THE SHIPMENT IT WAS NOT SUSPECT AS BEING DANGEROUS GOODS UNTIL THE WORDS FLAMMABLE AND UN1866 WERE NOTICED ON THE INNER METAL CONTAINER.  I NOTIFIED MARK HANSON OF THE MIA/CASFO TO REPORT THE INCIDENT, AND HE WAS TO INVESTIGATE.  THE PACKAGE WAS HELD PENDING HIS INVESTIGATION.

column168: THIS ENTIRE WOOD BOX SHIPMENT WAS NOTICED TO BE GIVING OFF A STRONG ODOR DURING THE SORTING OPERATION.  ONE EMPLOYEE COMPLAINED OF LUNG IRRITATION BECAUSE OF THE ODOR, AND ONE DG SPILL SPECIALIST ALSO COMPLAINED OF IRRITATION WHILE TRYING TO SECURE THE AREA.  NUMEROUS PERSONS IN THE SORT BUILDING WERE EVACUATED UNTIL THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT COULD BE PHYSICALLY REMOVED FROM THE BUILDING.  EACH OF THE WOOD CRATES WERE LATER OPENED AND THE INNER DRUMS WERE NOTICED TO HAVE SOME DAMAGE TO THE CLOSURES.  THE METAL DRUMS WERE PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS TO CONTAIN THE ODOR.  THE CONSIGNEE WAS CONTACTED REGARDING THE SHIPMENT AND IT WAS LATER TRUCKED TO THE DESTINATION.  BOTH EMPLOYEES, SHELIA BARNES AND STACEY JOHNSON WERE OBSERVED AT A LOCAL HOSPITAL FACILITY AND WERE RELEASED.  BOTH RETURNED THE FOLLOWING DAY WITHOUT MISSING ANY WORK.

column168: E.M.I. JOB NUMBER: 14989 A DOUBLE STACKED PALLET CONTAINING 5-GALLON PAILS CRUSHED THE LOWER PALLET OF PAILS. EIGHT 5-GALLON PAILS WERE CRUSHED, HOWEVER ONLY TWO LEAKED APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF LIQUID. A HAZMAT TEAM UNLOADED THE FREIGHT AND OVERPACKED THE DAMAGED PAILS. THEY BROKE UP THE CONTAINMATED PALLET AND PLACED IT INTO A DRUM FOR DISPOSAL ALONG WITH SOME CONTAMINATED PLASTIC AND CARDBOARD. THE DRUM WAS TAKEN OFF SITE THAT DAY FOR DISPOSAL. IT COULD NOT BE DETERMINED WHETHER OR NOT A LOAD SHIFT MAY HAVE CAUSED THE PAILS TO BE CRUSHED OR WHETHER THE WEIGHT OF THE PALLETS WERE JUST TOO HEAVY TO DOUBLE STACK.

column168: E.M.I. JOB # 14988  A 300-GALLON TOTE TANK OF COPPER TETRAMINE DICHLORIDE HAD LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 1-GALLON OF PRODUCT ONTO THE NOSE OF TRAILER # 27703. THE LID WAS LOOSE AND THE PRODUCT SLOSHED OUT DURING TRANSIT. CACTUS ENVIRONMENTAL PERSONNEL PLACED ABSORBENT MEDIA ON THE SPILL AND NEUTRALIZED ANY REMAINING FREE PRODUCT. THE ABSORBENT MEDIA WAS CLEANED UP AND PLACED INTO A 15-GALLON POLY DRUM FOR DISPOSAL. THE CAP WAS REPAIRED AND RETIGHTENED ON THE LEAKING TOTE. THE CAPS WERE CHECKED AND TIGHTENED ON THE OTHER TOTES.

DURING THE PM LOAD OPERATIONS THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE LEAKED SOME OF THE INNER CONTENTS. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED 12 PLASTIC INNER UNITS WITH ONE THAT THE CAP HAD BECOME LOOSE ALLOWING A SMALL LEAK, THE SHIPMENT WAS NOT MARKED, LABELED OR DOCUMENTED TO CONTAIN DANGEROUS GOODS. THE INNER UNITS APPEARED TO BE VARIOUS CORROSIVE MATERIALS. THE LOCAL FAA OFFICE WAS NOTIFIED AND THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

DION RESPONDED TO A CALL IN OB 1 BAY 275.  DECISION TREE LED HIM TO CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET.  PPE WAS DONNED.  SODIUM BICARBONATE WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILL.  IT WAS RETURNED AND PROCESSED THRU THE DMP.  TEMP ID 02-25-14TA,B

column168: T/C DODX-14306, LOAD FUEL, AVIATION, TURBINE ENGINE, WAS FOUND BY CAR INSPECTOR TO BE DRIPPING PRODUCT OUT OF BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE IN QUEENSGATE YARD.  AREA ISOLATED AND BUCKET PLACED UNDER BOTTOM OUTLET TO CATCH PRODUCT DRIPPING AT A RATE OF TWO (S) DROPS PER MINUTE. IN ADDITION, THE OUTLET NOZZLE EXTENSION WAS TIGHTENED. CAR SECURED AND RELEASED FOR DESTINATION. ONE QUART OF PRODUCT LOST. DEPARTMENT OF DEFENSE FLEET COORDINATOR, DALLAS BOWAN, WAS CONTACTED BY CSXT HAZMAT MGR., HARRY HOPES, REGARDING NON-ACCIDENTAL RELEASE.

E.M.I. JOB NUMBER: 14749 WHILE UNLOADING A TRAILER USING A FORKLIFT, TWO TEN G. DRUMS WERE DAMAGED BY THE FORKS RESULTING IN A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 20 OUNCES. THE DAMAGED DRUMS WERE PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS. ALL OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED. THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS AS WELL DUE TO THE FACT THAT THE CHEMICAL HAD IMPACTED THEM. NO PERSONNEL WERE AFFECTED BY THE RELEASE. CAUTION AND PROPER SAFETY RULES MUST BE FOLLOWED WHEN USING FORK TRUCKS TO MOVE FREIGHT.

column168: STEVE HARRELSON, HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT/HAZMAT, REPORT TANKCAR TILX 290095 WAS LEAKING TWO TO THREE GALLONS OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID A MINUTE AT THE BASIN YARD AND WAS LOCATED NEAR THE 8000 BLOCK OF CLINTON DRIVE TWO TO THREE TRACKS OVER FROM THE STREET. MR. HARRELSON REQUESTED A FAX BE SENT ON THE CONTENTS OF THE TANKCAR. FRANK LERCH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. MANAGER LERCH REPORTED PRODUCT HAD LEAKED FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE AND THAT THE LEAK HAD BEEN STOPPED BY GAGGING THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE. IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS OF PRODUCT HAD BEEN RELEASED, WITH NO POOLING OF PRODUCT. THE TANKCAR WAS MOVED TO KINDER MORGAN'S LOADING  RACK TO BE OFF LOADED. MGR. LERCH MADE CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER. NOVA CHEMICAL AND WAS ADVISED THAT JOEL GALE, TECHNICAL ADVISOR WAS EN ROUTE TO THE SCENE.  KINDER MORGAN IN A GOOD FAITH EFFORT CONTACTED BOOTS AND COOTS ENVIRONMENTAL TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE. UPON ARRIVAL OF BOOTS AND COOTS AND NOVA CHEMICAL PERSONNEL, AN ASSESSMENT WAS MADE AS TO THE CORRECT REMEDIAL ACTION TO BE TAKEN. PLASTIC SHEETING AND OIL ABSORBENT MATERIAL WERE APPLIED TO TEMPORARILY CONTAIN THE ODOR UNTIL ARRANGEMENTS COULD BE MADE TO RECOVER THE SPILLED MATERIAL. ON 02/11/02, UPRR REGIONAL MANAGER TIM O'BRIEN IN COMPANY WITH THE TNRCC, JOEL GALE OF NOVA CHEMICAL AND BOOTS & COOTS ENVIRONMENTAL ASSESSED THE SPILL SITE.  THE IMPACTED AEA WAS EVACUATED AND THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS DISPOSED OF BY BOOTS & COOTS ENVIRONMENTAL. THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS NOT ENOUGH OUTAGE ALLOWED IN THE CAR TO COMPENSATE  FOR PRODUCT EXPANSION AS THE RESULT OF TEMPERATURE CHANGES BETWEEN ALBERTA, CANADA, WHERE THE CAR WAS LOADED, AND DESTINATION AT GALENA PARK, TEXAS. THERE WERE NO DRAINS OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED NOR ANY REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

JAMES QUINTON, MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED TANKCAR GATX 11555 WAS LEAKING AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF CAUSTIC SODA FROM THE TOP OF THE TANKCAR, BUT HAD NOT LEAKED ANY PRODUCT ONTO THE GROUND. MR. QUINTON STATED THE TANKCAR WAS LOCATED AT THE SETTEGEST YARD IN HOUSTON ON TRACK 317. FRANK LERCH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED. MGR. LERCH INSPECTED THE CAR AND DETERMINED THAT THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY WAS NOT FULLY INTACT. THE PLASTIC DEFLECTOR WAS MISSING AND THERE WAS NO RUPTURE DISK WITHIN THE ASSEMBLY. LERCH TEMPORARILY SECURED THE CAR FROM ANY FURTHER RELEASE OF MATERIAL AND HAD IT SPOTTED AT THE CAB TRACK FOR FURTHER HANDLING. CONTACT HAD BEEN MADE WITH THE SHIPPER FERMOSA PLASTICS, DON HYPOLITE, TRAFFIC MANAGER AND HE DISPATCHED TWO TECHNICIANS TO THE SCENE. AT APPROXIMATELY 1315 HRS, FERMOSA TECHNICIANS TONY WHITLEY & NEAL FORSING ARRIVED ON SCENE NEUTRALIZED THE SIDES OF THE CAR AND REPAIRED THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY. AT 1700 HRS ALL NECESSARY CORRECTIVE ACTION HAD BEEN TAKEN, AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. THERE WERE NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS  OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

SHANE HOLTZ, LEAD CARMAN, REPORTED TANKCAR GLNX 23001 WAS VENTING A BLACK MIST AND ADVISED SOME MATERIAL HAD SPILLED DOWN THE SIDES OF THE TANKCAR. HE REPORTED THE TANKCAR WAS LOCATED AT THE SOUTH END OF TRACK NUMBER TWENTY ONE IN THE ROPER YARD. HARRY RODABOUGH, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. MGR. RODABOUGH REPORTED ALL THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND THE GASKET WAS THREE QUARTERS OF THE WAY MISSING. MR. RODABOUGH REPLACED THE GASKET WITH A TEMPORARY GORTEX GASKET AND TIGHTENED AND SECURED THE BOLTS. CHEM TREC WAS NOTIFIED.

LYNDON RAPHAEL, MANAGER TERMINAL OPERATIONS, REPORTED TANKCAR JRSX 1159 RELEASED VAPORS. MR. RAPHAEL STATED THE TANKCAR WAS LOCATED AT THE OGDEN YARD IN OGDEN, UTAH. HARRY RODABOUGH, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. HIS INSPECTION REVEALED MOST OF THE MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. THE BOLTS WERE SECURED, AND THE CAR WAS WASHED DOWN AND RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

MR. JOHNSON STATED ROBERT BAVIER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, WAS ON THE SCENE AND THE LEAK APPEARED TO BE ONGOING. MR. JOHNSON ALSO STATED THE INVOLVED SHIPPER HAD A SOLID STRING OF TANKCARS ON TRACK NUMBER 114 AND THE FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION WAS REQUIRING PERSONNEL TO INSPECT EACH TANKCAR FOR EXCESSIVE AMOUNTS OF PRESSURE. MR. JOHNSON ALSO STATED THE OLYMPIC COMMAND CENTER HAD BEEN NOTIFIED AND INFORMED RMCC TO NOTIFY BROCK NELSON, DIRECTOR OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, CHEMTREC, AND THE APPROPRIATE STATE AGENCIES. THE APPROPRIATE PERSONNEL WERE NOTIFIED. MIKE JOHNSON, MANAGER  OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, REPORTED THAT HE AND ROBERT BAVIER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, HAD SECURED THE WASHOUT PLATE AND THE LEAK STOPPED. column168: ROBERT BAVIER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, REPORTED HE AND MIKE JOHNSON, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, REPAIRED TANKCAR RWTX 21010, A LOAD OF PHOSPHORIC ACID. MGR. BAVIER REPORTED THAT A DEFECTIVE MANWAY GASKET HAD CAUSED APPROXIMATE ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT TO BE RELEASED. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED. CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.

DEAN COOPER, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, REPORTED ICTF SECURITY DISCOVERED A LEAKING CONTAINER MOLU 285579 WHICH CONTAINED FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS. MR. COOPER REPORTED THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER,AND LESS THAN ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED ON THE PAVEMENT. THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED AND ISOLATED IN THE CONTAINMENT AREA AT THE CUSTOMS DOCK. THE LADING CONSISTED OF 78 DRUMS, DOUBLE STACKED, AND SECURED WITH TY-PATCH. THE LAST ROW OF DRUMS AT THE REAR DOOR CONSISTED OF 3 PER ROW, WHICH IS CONSISTENT WITH THE TY-PATCH REQUIREMENTS, HOWEVER, THE FRONT FIVE ROWS OF DRUMS WERE BAYED OUT WITH 4 DRUMS PER ROW. THIS IS NOT CONSISTENT WITH TY-PATCH APPLICATIONS. MR. COOPER REQUESTED RMCC TO CONTACT CHEMTREC FOR SHIPPER CONTACT,AND MAKE COURTESY NOTIFICATIONS TO THE STATE AND LOS ANGELES CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT.  JOE, CHEMTREC, WAS NOTIFIED AND STATED THAT MITSUI OSK LINES AMERICA IS NOT LISTED WITH CHEMTREC. JOE ADVISED THAT THE CORRECT SHIPPER WAS SILBON OUT OF MICHIGAN.  JOE REPORTED HE CONTACTED JEFF DIETRICH, MITSUI OSK LINES AMERICA, OUT OF SACRAMENTO AND HE COULD BE REACHED AT 415-836-3505. MGR. COOPER SPOKE WITH JEFF DIETRICH, MISUI OSK LINES AMERICA, AND HE CONFIRMED THE SHIPPER TO BE SILLBON. MR. COOPER CONTACTED SILBON REPRESENTATIVE CARL MCLAUGHLIN, AT 517-436-3574. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO REMOVE THE DRUMS AND INSPECT FOR LEAKAGE. WHILE REMOVING THE DRUMS, LOCATION A SINGLE DRUM ON THE BOTTOM TIER NEAR THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER THAT WAS WEEPING  PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM CHIME OF THE DRUM. THERE WAS NO APPARENT WEAR OR DAMAGE FROM ADJACENT DRUM CONTACT. IT APPEARS THE BOTTOM CHIME CRIMP WAS DEFECTIVE, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE. ESTIMATED ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT WAS LOST DURING TRANSIT. THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO AN OVER PACK FOR SECUREMENT, AND TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE MANUFACTURER, PER THEIR REQUEST. THE CONTAINER WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE,THE DRUMS PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER,AND PROPERLY SECURED FOR FURTHER TRANSPORTATION.

column168: ON OR ABOUT 1030 AM 02/26/02 JIM MURPHY CALLED IN WITH A HAZMAT SPILL. DRIVER WAS AT HIS FIRST STOP IN CLARKSVILLE, INDIANA (MACK TRUCK SALES) WHEN HE NOTICE LIQUID LEAKING OUT OF THE TRAILER, IMMEDIATELY HE CALLED ME (JOSEPH WILLIBAUM DISTRICT MANAGER) AND EXPLAINED WHAT WAS GOING ON. AT THAT TIME THE CONSIGNEE (MACK TRUCK SALES) CALLED THE JEFFERSONVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT TO THE SCENE, WHICH IN TURN CALLED INDIANA DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION. BOTH WAS AT THE INCIDENT SITE AND WE BOTH CONTACTED CHEMC-TECH TO NOTIFIED THEM OF THE SITUATION. I (JOSEPH WILLIBAUM) CALLED THE SHIPPER TO HAVE THEM FAX THE MSD SHEETS TO USE. WHEN THE MSD SHEETS ARRIVED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT PLUG THE TOTE TO STOP THE LEAKING AND ALSO WASHED DOWN THE AREA WHERE THE SPILL OCCURRED TO THE REGULATIONS. THE SPILL WAS CAUSED DUE TO POOR LOADING. WHEN OTHER FREIGHT SHIFTED FORWARD IT POKED A SMALL HOLE IN THE TOTE. MID-STATES SAFETY DEPARTMENT WAS CONTACTED BY JOE AS SOON AS THE INCIDENT OCCURRED AND STAYED IN TOUCH THROUGH OUT THE WHOLE INCIDENT. THE SHIPPER VOPAK USA, INC. WAS VERY HELPFUL IN SOLVING THE SPILL. AS THE DISTRICT MANAGER FOR MID-STATE EXPRESS IN LOUISVILLE I'VE HAD A MEETING WITH ALL DRIVERS, DOCK PERSONNEL, AND SUPERVISOR ABOUT THE PROPER HANDLING OF HAZ-MAT FREIGHT TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS.

RESPONDED TO THE LEAKING PACKAGE WITH MY PPE AND SPILL CART WEARING MY APRON AND GLOVES. I THEN PROCEEDED TO PLACE THE SPILLED HAZARD IN A SPILL TRAY. ALL OF THE LEAKAGE WAS RETAINED IN THE BOX WHICH WENT TO THE MALLENKRODT CAGE. THE SALVAGEABLE PORTION WAS PLACED IN A YELLOW DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.
I RESPONDED TO BAY 294. I USED MY DECISION TREE & RESPONSE SHEETS FOR A FLAMMABLE LIQUID. I THEN PROCESSED THE ENTIRE CONTENTS THROUGH THE DMP, NO REMAINING BAL. TEMP ID#02-22-03N

column168: LARRY WILDER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, REPORTED A LOAD OF RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL ENTERED THE INBOUND GATE AT GLOBAL ONE YARD, 1400 SOUTH WESTERN BOULEVARD, AND THE CONTAINER WAS DETERMINED TO BE GIVING OFF HEAT.  MR. WILDER ADVISED CONTAINER TRLU 902728, UN 2916, CLASS 7, RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL YELLOW III, STCC: 4929151, COBALT 60.  THIS WAS A CONTAINER ON A TRUCK CHASSIS, AND WAS NOT LEAKING.  THE LOAD WAS DESTINED FOR SINGAPORE VIA, OAKLAND, CA..  MR. WILDER ADVISED CHICAGO FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD BEEN CONTACTED FOR RESPONSE TO THE YARD.  MR. WILDER STATED THIS WAS A LEVEL THREE INCIDENT AND REQUESTED A SPECIAL AGENT RESPOND IMMEDIATELY.  MR. WILDER REQUESTED NOTIFICATION OF MARK REIMERS, REGIONAL MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, AND REQUESTED STATE AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS BE MADE.  MR. WILDER ADVISED THAT THERE WAS NO EVACUATION OF THE YARD AT THE PRESENT TIME AND FURTHER ADVISED THAT THE TRAILER HAD BEEN ISOLATED.  KENT JONES, SPECIAL AGENT, WAS NOTIFIED AND ARRIVED ON SCENE. AT 03:13 PM, MGR. WILDER REPORTED CHICAGO FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON SCENE AND HAD ORDERED GLOBAL ONE YARD SHUT DOWN.  AT 03:36 PM, MGR. WILDER ADVISED THAT THERE WAS A MINOR EVACUATION INSIDE THE YARD.  THE EVACUATION WAS TO KEEP EMPLOYEES IN PLACE IN SIDE OF THE YARD OFFICE AT G1.  THIS EFFECTED ABOUT 12 TO 15 EMPLOYEES.  THE EVACUATION LASTED FOR 1 HOUR 30 MINUTES.  AT 4:02 PM, SHAWN, CHEMTREC, WAS NOTIFIED AND HE STATED THE EMERGENCY CONTACT FOR SHIPPER, AMERICAN PRESIDENT LINES, WOULD BE NOTIFIED TO CONTACT RMCC. THE CHICAGO FIRE DEPT, CHICAGO EPA, AND LARRY WILDER MEET WITH APL REPS ON SCENE AT G1.  THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER WAS CALLED AND CONFERENCED INTO A CALL WITH LARRY WILDER AND CHICAGO FIRE DEPT AND CHICAGO EPA.  CORRECT INFORMATION ABOUT THE MATERIAL AND SHIPMENT ROUTE WAS RECEIVED.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE HEAT RANGE WAS WITHIN NORMAL LIMITS.  THE CONTAINER WAS SEALED AND CLOSED PROPERLY BY THE SHIPPER.  THERE WAS NO LEAKING/RELEASE OF THE PRODUCT.  AT 04:19 PM, MGR WILDER REPORTED AFTER FURTHER TESTING WITH THE CITY OF CHICAGO ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY OFFICE AND THE CHICAGO FIRE DEPARTMENT, THE MATERIAL TESTED WAS FOUND TO BE WITHIN NORMAL TOLERANCE LIMITS AND THE SCENE WAS SECURE AT THIS TIME.  MR. WILDER FURTHER ADVISED GLOBAL ONE YARD WAS IN NORMAL OPERATIONS AT THIS TIME AND THERE WAS NO DISCHARGE OF PRODUCT.  MR. WILDER ADVISED HE REJECTED THE LOAD DUE TO ERRORS IN THE PAPERWORK.  AT 05:17 PM, MGR. WILDER REPORTED THE PAPERWORK WAS CORRECTED AND THE LOAD WAS ACCEPTED FOR SHIPMENT BY UP.

column168: I RESPONDED TO A SPILL ON THE ORANGE BELT. I USE THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR UNKNOWN. RESPONSE SHEET FOR UNKNOWN HAD ME PERFORM A LITMUS TEST. LITMUS TEST READ PH BALANCE RANGE NEUTRAL. RESPONSE SHEET AND RESULT OF LITMUS TEST HAD ME USE RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID. RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID HAD ME ABSORB ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WITH CLAY ABSORBENT ALL THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS PLACE IN A LINED SPILL TRAY AND AFTERWARDS ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS TAKEN TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID WAS LOST FROM THE PLASTIC CONTAINER AND THEREFORE BOTH PLASTIC CONTAINERS WERE SENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. A TIGHTER CAP COULD HAVE PREVENTED THE SPILL.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 12:30 P.M. ON TUESDAY FEBRUARY 19, 2002 I WAS NOTIFIED THAT JASON NAU HAD PUNCTURED A DRUM ON HIS TRAILER. THE MATERIAL THAT WAS RELEASED WAS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O.S.(ACETONE, TOLUENE) AND APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS WAS RELEASED IN THE BACK OF HIS TRAILER. WHEN JASON NAU WAS LOADING A DRUM OF WASTE ONTO THE TRAILER HE PUNCTURED IT WITH THE DRUM CART HE WAS USING. JASON MOVED THE DRUM TO THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER AND PUT IT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM TO CONTAIN THE MATERIAL IN THE DRUM. JASON THEN DROVE BACK TO THE BOBOLINK LOCATION BEFORE CLEANING UP THE BACK OF HIS TRAILER. WHILE DRIVING BACK TO THE PLANT A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL SPRAYED OUT THE BACK OF HIS TRAILER, THE MATERIAL SPRAYED ON A VAN THAT WAS FOLLOWING THE TRUCK. THE PERSON DRIVING THE VAN CALLED INTO OUR FACILITY TO REPORT IT. THIS WAS THE FIRST TIME WE WERE INFORMED THERE WAS A PROBLEM. THE NAME OF THE DRIVER OF THE VAN IS BRETT NEWKIRK, HIS PHONE NUMBER IS 414-771-4249. PAUL HAGMANN AND I DID GO TO HIS HOUSE TO CHECK THE VAN OUT AND THERE WERE LITTLE SPECKLES OF PAINT ALL OVER HIS VAN. I TOLD HIM THAT WE WILL CALL HIM BACK AND LET HIM KNOW WHAT OUR COMPANY WAS GOING TO DO, BUT WE WOULD MAKE SURE THAT HIS VAN WAS TAKEN CARE OF PROPERLY AND WE WOULD CORRECT THE PROBLEM OUR DRIVER HAD CAUSED. I CALLED BACK BRETT ON FEBRUARY 20, 2002 AT 8:00 A.M. AND I GAVE HIM THE NAME OF THE PERSON(MIKE KRUEGER) TO SPEAK WITH AND GAVE HIM THE TELEPHONE NUMBER TO REFLECTIONS AUTO BODY AT 1804 E. LAYTON AVE., MILWAUKEE. AFTER JASON GOT BACK TO THE BOBOLINK LOCATION HE NOTIFIED LARRY DIETRICH OF THE MISHAP. LARRY INFORMED JASON TO START CLEANING THE BACK OF HIS TRAILER ALONG WITH BILL GRULKOWSKI. THE WASTE MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP USING ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND DISPOSED OF IT AS A HAZARDOUS WASTE. AT ABOUT 3:45 P.M. I CALLED THE RELEASE INTO THE WISCONSIN SPILL REPORT NUMBER 1-800-943-0003 THE PERSON WHO ANSWERED TOOK  MY NAME AND PHONE NUMBER. HE TOLD ME HIS NAME WAS CHAD ROSS. I EXPLAINED TO HIM WHAT HAD HAPPENED AND THAT NO ONE WAS INJURED. THE WASTE MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED IN THE BACK OF THE TRAILER,  BUT I DID THINK A VERY SMALL AMOUNT HAD LEAKED OUT THE BACK OF THE TRAILER. I TOLD HIM APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS HAD RELEASED FROM THE DRUM. AT NO TIME DID THE WASTE COME IN CONTACT WITH ANY WATER OR SOIL. THERE WERE NO INJURIES. I ALSO NOTIFIED THE FEDERAL AGENCY AT 4:01 P.M. AND TALK TO MS. JOHNSON. I EXPLAINED THAT IT WAS ALL CONTAINED INSIDE ONE OF OUR TRAILERS, OUR TRAILERS, BUT I DID THINK A VERY SMALL AMOUNT LEAKED OUT ONTO HWY 45. SHE ASKED ME IF I KNEW OF THE MILE MARKER WHERE IT COULD HAVE LEAKED OUT, I SAID I REALLY DON'T KNOW. SHE ALSO ASKED ME WHAT SIZE THE TRAILER WAS AND I TOLD HER THE TRAILER HELD 88-55 GALLON DRUMS. THE RELEASE WAS CLEANED UP AND WE DID NOT REQUIRE ANY HELP FROM OUTSIDE OUR COMPANY. SHE THEN GAVE ME A CASE NUMBER OF 594447.
XSW DSR DARR IN LYONS WAS LOADING DOOR 87.  HE HAD THE ABOVE PRO ON A SKID TAKING TO TRAILER.  ONE BOX FELL OFF THE SKID AND THE TOP TO ONE CONTAINER CAME OFF.
